Moreover, the emphasis on *pragmatic stealth*—producing adversarial examples that are not only fluent and grammatical but also rhetorically plausible—is a new dimension of attack realism. Classifiers increasingly rely on discourse cues for high-stakes tasks like misinformation detection (as seen in FakeNewsNet, ISOT), yet defenses remain largely unaware of such structural vulnerabilities. Thus, Idea 1 exposes a critical blind spot in robustness evaluation frameworks.

While both ideas score high in clarity and feasibility, Idea 1 offers a more groundbreaking contribution by shifting the adversarial paradigm from syntax to discourse, opening a new axis of research in neuro-symbolic adversarial NLP. It is therefore more likely to constitute a significant, publishable advance at top-tier venues like ACL, EMNLP, or CCS.

